Been introduced to motogp since young age, i was priviledged to see your debut as a teammate to Rossi -who later be my fav rider of all time- until at one point, 2006 season. Where things didn't worked for Rossi, this Kentucky Kid was able to push the title decider till the last circuit on the calendar. Heading onto Valencia with Rossi's 8 pts advantage, i couldn't dare to missed the race. Everything went well, until Rossi's bike went down weirdly -as it seems to me- at the same time, i had family gathering planned and was forced to go out. But as cringy as it gets, i shouted to my dad.I insisted to watch the race, and won't go anywhere. Turns out, i didn't have the strength to fight -damn i missed a race this season-. It's over for Rossi i thought. And it did. I refused to talk with anyone in the family until i went back home and saw this photo of yours. It led me to a conclusion that, to achieve such things, when you are clearly the underdog infront of everyone was not easy and need hardwork. Now, Motogp becoming more popular than it was back then, so everyone has their own man to look up onto. Valencia 2006 really change the way how i see things. before that, anyone else but Rossi are enemies.Its been a pleasure to watch the other rider challenging Rossi nowadays with dignity and true sportmanship -someone never had it 99,3-. Just like what you did that season. That's the first time where i felt so stupid as individuals. Thanks for the Oct.29.2006. All the best for you, Kato, Shoya, Lenz, and Simoncelli. Race In Peace.
.
.
#RideOnKentuckyKid
